{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2017,"question":"If 2 mol of H₂ reacts with 1 mol of O₂, how many moles of H₂O are produced?","options":["2","1","4","0.5"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O. Mole ratio H₂:H₂O = 1:1 → 2 mol H₂O."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2018,"question":"What is the oxidation state of S in H₂SO₄?","options":["+6","+4","+8","-2"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2(+1)+x+4(-2)=0 → 2+x-8=0 → x=+6."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2019,"question":"The number of moles of ions in 1 mole of NaCl is:","options":["2","1","3","4"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NaCl dissociates into Na⁺ and Cl⁻ → 2 moles of ions."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2020,"question":"Which of the following has the highest number of molecules? (H=1, C=12, O=16)","options":["36 g H₂O","44 g CO₂","16 g CH₄","46 g C₂H₅OH"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Moles: H₂O=36/18=2; CO₂=44/44=1; CH₄=16/16=1; C₂H₅OH=46/46=1. H₂O has most moles (2)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2021,"question":"The percentage by mass of nitrogen in NH₃ is: (N=14, H=1)","options":["82.35%","17.65%","50%","75%"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Molar mass NH₃=17. N% = (14/17)×100 = 82.35%."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2022,"question":"A 0.1 M solution of H₂SO₄ has an H⁺ ion concentration of:","options":["0.2 M","0.1 M","0.05 M","0.4 M"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"H₂SO₄ → 2H⁺ + SO₄²⁻. [H⁺] = 2×0.1 = 0.2 M."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2023,"question":"What is the volume of 0.5 mol of O₂ at STP?","options":["11.2 L","22.4 L","44.8 L","5.6 L"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"0.5 × 22.4 = 11.2 L."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2024,"question":"How many grams of NaCl are needed to prepare 500 mL of 0.2 M solution? (Na=23, Cl=35.5)","options":["5.85 g","11.7 g","2.925 g","58.5 g"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Moles = 0.2×0.5 = 0.1. Mass = 0.1×58.5 = 5.85 g."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2025,"question":"A hydrocarbon contains 85.7% C and 14.3% H. What is its empirical formula? (C=12, H=1)","options":["CH₂","CH₃","C₂H₄","C₃H₆"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"C:85.7/12=7.14; H:14.3/1=14.3; ratio 1:2 → CH₂."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2026,"question":"The molarity of a solution containing 4.0 g of NaOH in 250 cm³ is: (Na=23, O=16, H=1)","options":["0.4 M","0.1 M","1.0 M","0.2 M"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Moles NaOH = 4/40=0.1. V=0.25 L. C=0.1/0.25=0.4 M."},

// ============================================================
// SECTION 3: GAS LAWS & KINETIC THEORY (Q181–Q230)
// ============================================================
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2000,"question":"Boyle"s law states that at constant temperature, the volume of a gas is:","options":["Inversely proportional to pressure","Directly proportional to pressure","Independent of pressure","Directly proportional to temperature"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Boyle: PV = k (V ∝ 1/P)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2001,"question":"Charles"s law relates volume and:","options":["Temperature (Kelvin)","Pressure","Mass","Density"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Charles: V ∝ T (at constant P)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2002,"question":"The ideal gas equation is:","options":["PV = nRT","PV = NkT","Both","PV = RT"],"correctIndex":2,"explanation":"PV = nRT = NkT (where N = number of molecules)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2003,"question":"A gas occupies 2 L at 1 atm. What volume does it occupy at 2 atm (constant T)?","options":["1 L","4 L","0.5 L","2 L"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"P₁V₁ = P₂V₂ → 1×2 = 2×V₂ → V₂ = 1 L."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2004,"question":"A gas has a volume of 3 L at 300 K. What is the volume at 600 K (constant P)?","options":["6 L","1.5 L","3 L","12 L"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂ → 3/300 = V₂/600 → V₂=6 L."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2005,"question":"The pressure exerted by a gas is due to:","options":["Collisions of molecules with the walls","Molecular weight","Gravity","Intermolecular forces"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Gas pressure comes from molecular impacts on container walls."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2006,"question":"At STP, 1 mole of any gas occupies:","options":["22.4 L","24.4 L","22.4 m³","24.4 m³"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Molar volume at STP = 22.4 L (0°C, 1 atm)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2007,"question":"Which gas deviates most from ideal behavior at high pressure?","options":["NH₃","He","H₂","N₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NH₃ has strong intermolecular forces (H‑bonding), deviates most."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2008,"question":"The kinetic theory assumes that gas molecules:","options":["Have negligible volume","Have no intermolecular forces","Move in random motion","All of these"],"correctIndex":3,"explanation":"All are assumptions of the kinetic theory of ideal gases."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2009,"question":"What is the pressure of 0.5 mol of gas in a 10 L container at 300 K? (R=0.082 L·atm/mol·K)","options":["1.23 atm","2.46 atm","0.615 atm","4.92 atm"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"P = nRT/V = (0.5×0.082×300)/10 = 1.23 atm."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2010,"question":"The root mean square speed of gas molecules is directly proportional to:","options":["√T","T","1/√T","1/T"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"v_rms = √(3RT/M) → ∝ √T."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2011,"question":"Which of the following gases effuses the fastest?","options":["He","Ne","Ar","Kr"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Graham"s law: rate ∝ 1/√M. He has the smallest molar mass."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2012,"question":"Dalton"s law of partial pressure states that total pressure is the sum of:","options":["Partial pressures of individual gases","Volumes of individual gases","Masses of individual gases","Temperatures of individual gases"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dalton: P_total = P₁ + P₂ + ..."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2013,"question":"A mixture of gases at 1 atm has partial pressures: 0.3 atm O₂ and 0.4 atm N₂. What is the partial pressure of CO₂?","options":["0.3 atm","0.1 atm","0.4 atm","0.7 atm"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"P_total = 1 = 0.3+0.4+P_CO₂ → P_CO₂ = 0.3 atm."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2014,"question":"Which of the following is NOT a condition for ideal gas behavior?","options":["High pressure","Low pressure","High temperature","Large volume"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Ideal behavior is approached at low pressure and high temperature. High pressure causes deviations."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2015,"question":"Van der Waals equation corrects for:","options":["Molecular volume and intermolecular forces","Temperature and pressure","Mass and velocity","Energy and entropy"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The a term corrects for attraction, b term for molecular volume."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2016,"question":"A gas at 27°C has volume V. What is the volume at 127°C at constant pressure?","options":["(400/300)V","(300/400)V","2V","V/2"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"T₁=300K, T₂=400K. V₂ = (T₂/T₁)V = (400/300)V."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2017,"question":"At constant volume, the pressure of a gas is:","options":["Directly proportional to temperature","Inversely proportional to temperature","Independent of temperature","Proportional to volume"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Gay‑Lussac: P ∝ T (at constant V)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2018,"question":"A gas sample has a pressure of 2 atm at 300 K. What is the pressure at 600 K if volume is constant?","options":["4 atm","2 atm","1 atm","6 atm"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"P₁/T₁ = P₂/T₂ → 2/300 = P₂/600 → P₂ = 4 atm."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2019,"question":"The average kinetic energy of gas molecules depends on:","options":["Temperature only","Pressure only","Volume only","Molar mass"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"KE_avg = (3/2)RT, depends only on temperature."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2020,"question":"Which of the following is a real gas that behaves ideally at low pressure?","options":["Any gas","Only noble gases","Only H₂","Only He"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"At low pressure, all gases approach ideal behavior."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2021,"question":"The gas with the highest rate of diffusion is:","options":["H₂","O₂","CO₂","Cl₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Rate ∝ 1/√M. H₂ has smallest molar mass (2 g/mol)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2022,"question":"If the volume of a gas is halved at constant temperature, the pressure:","options":["Doubles","Halves","Quadruples","Remains same"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Boyle"s law: P₁V₁ = P₂V₂ → V half → P doubles."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2023,"question":"A container holds 2 moles of N₂ and 3 moles of O₂. What is the mole fraction of N₂?","options":["0.4","0.6","0.5","0.2"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"X_N₂ = 2/(2+3) = 0.4."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2024,"question":"The compressibility factor Z = PV/nRT. For an ideal gas, Z =:","options":["1","0","∞",">1"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"For ideal gas, Z = 1. Deviations give Z≠1."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2025,"question":"Which gas has the highest critical temperature?","options":["H₂O","CO₂","H₂","He"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"H₂O has strong intermolecular forces → high critical temperature."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2026,"question":"At absolute zero, the volume of an ideal gas becomes:","options":["Zero","Infinite","Constant","Negative"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"V ∝ T; at 0 K, V = 0 (theoretical)."},

// ============================================================
// SECTION 4: ACIDS, BASES & SALTS (Q231–Q310)
// ============================================================
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2000,"question":"An acid is a substance that:","options":["Donates protons","Accepts protons","Donates electrons","Accepts electrons"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Bronsted‑Lowry: acid = proton donor."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2001,"question":"A base is a substance that:","options":["Accepts protons","Donates protons","Donates electrons","Accepts electrons"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Bronsted‑Lowry: base = proton acceptor."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2002,"question":"Which of the following is a strong acid?","options":["HCl","CH₃COOH","H₂CO₃","H₂S"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"HCl is a strong acid (fully dissociates)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2003,"question":"Which of the following is a weak base?","options":["NH₃","NaOH","KOH","Ba(OH)₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NH₃ is a weak base (partial ionisation)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2004,"question":"The pH of a 0.01 M HCl solution is:","options":["2","1","3","4"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"HCl is strong acid, [H⁺]=0.01 M, pH = -log(0.01)=2."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2005,"question":"What is the pH of a 0.001 M NaOH solution?","options":["11","3","12","10"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"pOH = -log(0.001)=3; pH = 14-3=11."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2006,"question":"The salt formed from a strong acid and a weak base is:","options":["Acidic","Basic","Neutral","Amphoteric"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"e.g., NH₄Cl (strong acid HCl + weak base NH₃) → acidic salt."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2007,"question":"Which of the following salts will produce a basic solution when dissolved in water?","options":["Na₂CO₃","NH₄Cl","NaCl","KNO₃"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Na₂CO₃ is salt of weak acid (H₂CO₃) and strong base (NaOH) → basic."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2008,"question":"The pH of a solution with [H⁺] = 1×10⁻⁵ M is:","options":["5","9","7","1"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"pH = -log(1×10⁻⁵)=5."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2009,"question":"In the titration of HCl with NaOH, the equivalence point has pH:","options":["7",">7","<7","0"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Strong acid + strong base → neutral salt → pH = 7."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2010,"question":"Which indicator changes colour at pH 8–10?","options":["Phenolphthalein","Methyl orange","Litmus","Methyl red"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Phenolphthalein: colourless below 8, pink above 10."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2011,"question":"A buffer solution resists changes in:","options":["pH","Temperature","Concentration","Pressure"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Buffer = weak acid/base + its salt, maintains pH."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2012,"question":"Which of the following is NOT a buffer?","options":["NaCl + HCl","CH₃COOH + CH₃COONa","NH₃ + NH₄Cl","H₂CO₃ + NaHCO₃"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NaCl + HCl is a strong acid + salt of strong acid; not a buffer."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2013,"question":"The conjugate base of HSO₄⁻ is:","options":["SO₄²⁻","H₂SO₄","HSO₃⁻","SO₃²⁻"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Conjugate base = acid minus H⁺."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2014,"question":"The conjugate acid of NH₃ is:","options":["NH₄⁺","NH₂⁻","NH₂OH","N₂H₄"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Conjugate acid = base + H⁺."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2015,"question":"Which of the following is amphiprotic?","options":["H₂O","HCl","NaOH","NaCl"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"H₂O can act as acid or base (donates or accepts H⁺)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2016,"question":"The salt formed when NaOH reacts with H₂SO₄ is:","options":["Na₂SO₄","NaHSO₄","Na₂SO₃","NaSO₄"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2NaOH + H₂SO₄ → Na₂SO₄ + 2H₂O (normal salt)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2017,"question":"A salt that contains water of crystallisation is called:","options":["Hydrated salt","Anhydrous salt","Double salt","Complex salt"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hydrated salts have water molecules in their crystal structure (e.g., CuSO₄·5H₂O)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2018,"question":"Which of the following is a deliquescent substance?","options":["NaOH","NaCl","CaCO₃","SiO₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NaOH absorbs moisture from air and dissolves in it (deliquescence)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2019,"question":"Which substance is hygroscopic but not deliquescent?","options":["Concentrated H₂SO₄","NaOH","CaCl₂","MgCl₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"H₂SO₄ absorbs water but does not dissolve to form a solution (does not deliquesce)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2020,"question":"The pH of a 0.1 M acetic acid (Ka=1.8×10⁻⁵) is approximately:","options":["2.87","4.76","1.0","5.0"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"[H⁺] = √(Ka×C) = √(1.8×10⁻⁵×0.1) = 1.34×10⁻³ M; pH = -log(1.34×10⁻³) = 2.87."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2021,"question":"Which of the following is a monobasic acid?","options":["HCl","H₂SO₄","H₃PO₄","CH₃COOH"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Monobasic = one ionizable H⁺ (HCl)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2022,"question":"A dibasic acid has how many replaceable hydrogen atoms?","options":["2","1","3","4"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Dibasic = two H⁺ ions per molecule (e.g., H₂SO₄)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2023,"question":"Which of the following is a basic oxide?","options":["Na₂O","CO₂","SO₂","P₂O₅"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Na₂O is a basic oxide (metal oxide). Others are acidic oxides."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2024,"question":"Which of the following is an acidic oxide?","options":["CO₂","CaO","MgO","Na₂O"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"CO₂ dissolves in water to form carbonic acid (acidic oxide)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2025,"question":"Amphoteric oxides react with both:","options":["Acids and bases","Only acids","Only bases","Salts"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Amphoteric oxides (e.g., Al₂O₃, ZnO) react with acids and bases."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2026,"question":"Which of the following is an example of an amphoteric oxide?","options":["Al₂O₃","Na₂O","CO₂","SO₃"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Al₂O₃ is amphoteric."},

// ============================================================
// SECTION 5: ELECTROCHEMISTRY & ELECTROLYSIS (Q311–Q380)
// ============================================================
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2000,"question":"Electrolysis is the decomposition of a compound by:","options":["Electric current","Heat","Light","Pressure"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Electrolysis uses electricity to drive a non‑spontaneous reaction."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2001,"question":"In electrolysis, the anode is the electrode where:","options":["Oxidation occurs","Reduction occurs","Neutralisation occurs","No reaction"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Anode attracts anions → oxidation (loss of electrons)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2002,"question":"The cathode is the electrode where:","options":["Reduction occurs","Oxidation occurs","Both","Neither"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cathode attracts cations → reduction (gain of electrons)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2003,"question":"During electrolysis of molten NaCl, the product at the cathode is:","options":["Na","Cl₂","Na⁺","Cl⁻"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Na⁺ + e⁻ → Na (reduction)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2004,"question":"During electrolysis of molten NaCl, the product at the anode is:","options":["Cl₂","Na","Na⁺","Cl⁻"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2Cl⁻ → Cl₂ + 2e⁻ (oxidation)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2005,"question":"A faraday is equal to:","options":["96500 C","96.5 C","9.65×10⁷ C","965 C"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"1 Faraday = charge on 1 mol of electrons = 96500 C."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2006,"question":"How many faradays are required to deposit 1 mol of Cu from Cu²⁺?","options":["2","1","3","4"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cu²⁺ + 2e⁻ → Cu → 2 faradays."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2007,"question":"In the electrolysis of brine (NaCl solution), the product at the cathode is:","options":["H₂","Cl₂","Na","O₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Water is reduced preferentially: 2H₂O + 2e⁻ → H₂ + 2OH⁻."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2008,"question":"The product at the anode during electrolysis of brine (using inert electrodes) is:","options":["Cl₂","O₂","H₂","NaOH"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2Cl⁻ → Cl₂ + 2e⁻ (chlorine gas)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2009,"question":"Which of the following is a strong electrolyte?","options":["NaCl","CH₃COOH","NH₃","Sugar"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"NaCl fully dissociates in water → strong electrolyte."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2010,"question":"The electrical conductivity of metals is due to:","options":["Delocalized electrons","Mobile ions","Protons","Neutrons"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Metals have free (delocalised) electrons that carry charge."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2011,"question":"In the electrochemical series, which metal is the strongest reducing agent?","options":["Li","K","Na","Ca"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Li has the most negative reduction potential → strongest reducing agent."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2012,"question":"Which of the following is displaced from its salt solution by copper?","options":["Ag","Zn","Fe","Pb"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cu is less reactive than Ag, so Cu + Ag⁺ → Cu²⁺ + Ag."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2013,"question":"A galvanic cell converts:","options":["Chemical energy to electrical energy","Electrical energy to chemical energy","Heat to chemical","Light to chemical"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Galvanic (voltaic) cells produce electricity from spontaneous reactions."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2014,"question":"The salt bridge in a galvanic cell allows:","options":["Flow of ions to maintain charge balance","Flow of electrons","Flow of current","Flow of protons"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Salt bridge completes the circuit by ion migration."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2015,"question":"The standard electrode potential of hydrogen is:","options":["0.00 V","1.00 V","-0.76 V","+0.34 V"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Standard hydrogen electrode (SHE) is assigned 0.00 V."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2016,"question":"Which of the following ions is reduced at the cathode during electrolysis of aqueous CuSO₄?","options":["Cu²⁺","H⁺","SO₄²⁻","OH⁻"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Cu²⁺ has a higher reduction potential than H⁺, so Cu²⁺ is reduced first."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2017,"question":"During electrolysis of dilute H₂SO₄ with Pt electrodes, the product at the anode is:","options":["O₂","H₂","SO₃","SO₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"OH⁻ → ½O₂ + H₂O + 2e⁻ (oxygen gas)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2018,"question":"The discharge potential of an ion depends on:","options":["Electrode potential and concentration","Only concentration","Only temperature","Only pressure"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Discharge depends on standard potential and ion concentration (Nernst equation)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2019,"question":"Which of the following will not undergo electrolysis?","options":["Solid NaCl","Molten NaCl","Aqueous NaCl","All can electrolyse"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Solid NaCl has no free ions; electrolysis requires mobile ions."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2020,"question":"In the electrolysis of aqueous NaCl, what is formed at the cathode?","options":["H₂","Na","Cl₂","O₂"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Water is reduced to H₂ (since Na⁺ is not easily reduced in water)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2021,"question":"The anode in an electrochemical cell is:","options":["Negative electrode in a galvanic cell, positive in electrolytic cell","Positive in both","Negative in both","Positive in galvanic, negative in electrolytic"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Anode = negative in galvanic (oxidation), positive in electrolytic (oxidation)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2022,"question":"A metal that is electroplated uses:","options":["Electrolysis","Galvanic cell","Neutralisation","Combustion"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Electroplating is done using electrolysis (deposition of metal ions)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2023,"question":"The number of moles of electrons required to deposit 1 mol of Al from Al³⁺ is:","options":["3","1","2","4"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Al³⁺ + 3e⁻ → Al → 3 faradays."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2024,"question":"In the electrolysis of CuSO₄ with copper electrodes, the mass of the anode:","options":["Decreases","Increases","Remains same","Dissolves completely"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Copper from anode dissolves as Cu²⁺ (anode loses mass)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2025,"question":"In the electrolysis of CuSO₄ with inert electrodes, the solution becomes:","options":["More acidic","More basic","Neutral","Unchanged"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"2H₂O → O₂ + 4H⁺ + 4e⁻ at anode; H⁺ increases → acidic."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2026,"question":"The Faraday constant is the charge on:","options":["1 mole of electrons","1 mole of protons","1 mole of ions","1 gram of electrons"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"1 F = charge on 1 mole of e⁻ = 96500 C."},

// ============================================================
// SECTION 6: THERMODYNAMICS & KINETICS (Q381–Q430)
// ============================================================
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2000,"question":"Exothermic reactions:","options":["Release heat","Absorb heat","Require catalyst","Are spontaneous always"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Exothermic = ΔH negative (heat released)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2001,"question":"Endothermic reactions:","options":["Absorb heat","Release heat","Have negative ΔH","Produce light"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Endothermic = ΔH positive (heat absorbed)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2002,"question":"The enthalpy change of a reaction depends on:","options":["Initial and final states","Pathway","Rate","Catalyst"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Enthalpy is a state function; ΔH depends only on initial and final states."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2003,"question":"The activation energy is the minimum energy required for:","options":["A reaction to occur","A bond to break","A catalyst to work","A gas to expand"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Activation energy is the energy barrier that reactants must overcome."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2004,"question":"A catalyst:","options":["Lowers activation energy","Increases activation energy","Changes ΔH","Is consumed in reaction"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Catalysts provide an alternative pathway with lower Ea."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2005,"question":"The rate of a reaction increases with temperature because:","options":["More molecules have energy > Ea","Molecules collide less","Concentration changes","Pressure decreases"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Higher T increases the fraction of molecules with sufficient energy."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2006,"question":"The law of mass action states that the rate is proportional to:","options":["Product of concentrations of reactants","Product of concentrations of products","Sum of concentrations","Square of concentrations"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Rate ∝ [A]^a[B]^b for elementary reactions."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2007,"question":"The order of a reaction is determined by:","options":["Experiment","Stoichiometry","Temperature","Pressure"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Reaction order is empirical, determined from experimental data."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2008,"question":"A zero‑order reaction has a rate that:","options":["Is independent of concentration","Doubles when concentration doubles","Is proportional to concentration","Is proportional to square of concentration"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Rate = k (independent of [reactant])."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2009,"question":"The half‑life of a first‑order reaction:","options":["Is independent of initial concentration","Depends on initial concentration","Is inversely proportional to initial concentration","Is directly proportional to initial concentration"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"t₁/₂ = 0.693/k (constant for first‑order)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2010,"question":"Which of the following increases the rate of a reaction?","options":["Increasing temperature","Adding catalyst","Increasing concentration","All of these"],"correctIndex":3,"explanation":"All increase reaction rate (except in some specific cases)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2011,"question":"The collision theory states that for a reaction to occur, molecules must:","options":["Collide with sufficient energy and correct orientation","Collide with any energy","Be in same phase","Have similar masses"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Effective collisions require energy ≥ Ea and proper geometry."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2012,"question":"In a reversible reaction at equilibrium, the rate of forward reaction equals:","options":["Rate of reverse reaction","Zero","Maximum","Infinity"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Equilibrium = dynamic balance of forward and reverse rates."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2013,"question":"Le Chatelier"s principle states that a system at equilibrium will:","options":["Respond to oppose a stress","Always shift to products","Always shift to reactants","Remain unchanged"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"The system adjusts to minimise the effect of an external change."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2014,"question":"If pressure is increased on a gaseous equilibrium, the system shifts toward:","options":["Fewer moles of gas","More moles of gas","No shift","The side with higher volume"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Increase pressure favours the side with fewer gas moles."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2015,"question":"For the equilibrium N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃, increasing temperature:","options":["Shifts to reactants (endothermic forward)","Shifts to products","No effect","Increases pressure"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Forward reaction is exothermic; increasing T shifts to reactants (absorbs heat)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2016,"question":"A catalyst affects equilibrium by:","options":["Increasing rate of both forward and reverse reactions equally","Shifting equilibrium to products","Shifting equilibrium to reactants","Changing ΔH"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Catalyst speeds up both directions equally; equilibrium position unchanged."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2017,"question":"The equilibrium constant Kc for a reaction depends on:","options":["Temperature","Concentration","Pressure","Volume"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Kc is constant at a given temperature."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2018,"question":"If Kc is large (>>1), the equilibrium:","options":["Favours products","Favours reactants","Is at middle","No reaction"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Large Kc → products dominate at equilibrium."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2019,"question":"The entropy of a system:","options":["Increases with disorder","Decreases with disorder","Is always zero","Is independent of temperature"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Entropy is a measure of randomness/disorder."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2020,"question":"For a spontaneous reaction, the Gibbs free energy change ΔG is:","options":["Negative","Positive","Zero","Undefined"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Spontaneous → ΔG < 0."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2021,"question":"ΔG = ΔH - TΔS. At high temperature, a reaction with positive ΔS becomes:","options":["More spontaneous","Less spontaneous","Unchanged","Non‑spontaneous"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"For ΔH positive, ΔS positive → spontaneous at high T."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2022,"question":"A reaction with ΔH > 0 and ΔS < 0 is:","options":["Non‑spontaneous at all temperatures","Spontaneous at all temperatures","Spontaneous only at low T","Spontaneous only at high T"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"ΔG = ΔH - TΔS → both terms positive → ΔG always positive."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2023,"question":"The enthalpy of combustion is always:","options":["Negative","Positive","Zero","Variable"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Combustion is exothermic → ΔH negative."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2024,"question":"Hess"s law states that enthalpy change depends only on:","options":["Initial and final states","Pathway","Number of steps","Catalyst"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Hess"s law: enthalpy is a state function."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2025,"question":"Bond breaking is:","options":["Endothermic","Exothermic","Neither","Both"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Breaking bonds requires energy (endothermic)."},
{"subject":"Chemistry","year":2026,"question":"Bond formation is:","options":["Exothermic","Endothermic","Neither","Both"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Forming bonds releases energy (exothermic)."},

